ned to her with a smile, ready to play on, but the smile faded: she was looking at him with narrowed eyes, biting her lip.

“Ten years,” she said bitterly. “You little fool! You really want to wait ten years?”

“That’s how it looks to me,” Franz replied. “I don’t know. Maybe, if I’m very lucky … but, for instance, take Mr. Piffke; he’s been with the store right from the start, and that’s you know how many years. But he lives very modestly. He doesn’t make more than fo